        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: The Munich Security Conference has made Europe reconsider its Transatlantic relationship with the United States.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">This year’s Munich security conference <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-02-2025-h1-1-set-a-precedent-in-us-europe-relations?source=website" target="_blank">set a precedent in US-European relations</a>. One notable event was JD Vance’s controversial speech. He critiqued the European leadership, accusing them of suppressing populist concerns, restricting speech, and failing to address migration. He argued that the true threat to Europe came from Europe’s internal retreat from some of its “most fundamental values.” EU and German officials didn’t receive the speech well.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">The US congressional envoy presented Zelenskyy with a document to sign stating that Ukraine would give the US half its mineral resources as compensation for its support, which Zelenskyy refused to sign. He said the document was too focused on US interests and didn’t provide any security guarantees in return.</p>
        </mj-text>
